text.Taxonomy and naming:
Verticordia etheliana was first formally described by Charles Gardner in 1942 and the description was published in the Journal of the Royal Society of Western Australia from specimens collected between "Yaringa" station and Northampton by William Blackall. The specific epithet (etheliana) honours Ethel Gray Blackall, the wife of the collector of the type specimens.When Alex George reviewed the genus Verticordia in 1991, he described two varieties of this species:
Verticordia etheliana C.A.Gardner  var. etheliana which has leaves which are 3–6 mm (0.1–0.2 in) long, flower stalks 6–10 mm (0.2–0.4 in) long, sepals 9–10 mm (0.35–0.39 in) long, petals 6–10 mm (0.2–0.4 in) long, and a style which is 16–20 mm (0.6–0.8 in);
Verticordia etheliana var. formosa  A.S.George  which shorter leaves, flower stalks, sepals, petals and styles than var. etheliana;.George placed this species in subgenus Eperephes, section Pennuligera along with V. comosa, V. lepidophylla, V. chrysostachys, V. dichroma, V. x eurardyensis, V. muelleriana, V. argentea, V. aereiflora, V. fragrans, V. venusta, V. forrestii, V. serotina, V. oculata, V. albida and V. grandis.
